The stories he wrote at this time were mainly gossip, myths about the

00:06:10.412 --> 00:06:14.762
European Union that he wrote because he knew they would appeal to the

00:06:15.042 --> 00:06:19.972
mostly elderly, conservative middle class readers of The Daily Telegraph.

00:06:21.172 --> 00:06:28.152
His journalistic career continued until 2001, when he first became a member of parliament

00:06:28.162 --> 00:06:34.732
for the very safe Conservative seat of Henley, an area just to the west of London.

00:06:35.912 --> 00:06:39.872
Although he was now an MP, he was now a member of

00:06:39.872 --> 00:06:43.402
parliament, he never really stopped being a journalist.

00:06:43.792 --> 00:06:48.662
He was still the editor of a right-wing magazine called The Spectator, a

00:06:48.662 --> 00:06:54.812
position he had been given in 1999 on the explicit condition that he didn’t

00:06:54.862 --> 00:07:01.452
become a politician, a promise which he broke in 2001 when he did exactly that.

00:07:02.772 --> 00:07:08.002
He was also still a columnist for The Daily Telegraph, writing a weekly

00:07:08.002 --> 00:07:15.912
column and being paid £250,000 a year, so that's over €300,000, to do so.

00:07:16.802 --> 00:07:23.512
The theme of being paid enough, of making enough money, will be a recurrent one throughout

00:07:23.562 --> 00:07:30.412
Johnson’s career because, despite coming from a wealthy family and earning what to

00:07:30.412 --> 00:07:36.452
most people would be significant amounts of money, for Johnson it was never enough.

00:07:36.912 --> 00:07:41.182
And this was mainly because he had a lot of expenses.

